@Tutorial(time: 15) {
    @Intro(title: "Define the Calculator Language") {
        Every Cambium grammar starts with a kind enumeration: one case per
        token and one per node the parser can produce. The kind enum
        becomes the `Kind` associated type of a ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage``
        conformance, and Cambium specializes its generic types around that
        language to make tree storage compact and traversal type-safe.

        In this tutorial you build the calculator's `CalculatorKind` enum
        with help from the ``CambiumSyntaxMacros/CambiumSyntaxKind()`` and
        ``CambiumSyntaxMacros/StaticText(_:)`` macros, then add a
        `CalculatorLanguage` conformance with the trivia and node/token
        classifiers Cambium needs to traverse the tree correctly.
    }

    @Section(title: "Sketch the kind enum") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            A `SyntaxKind`-conforming enum lives at the heart of every
            Cambium language. The macro
            ``CambiumSyntaxMacros/CambiumSyntaxKind()`` derives the
            conformance so all you have to write is the cases.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Create `CalculatorLanguage.swift` with an empty
                `UInt32`-backed enum decorated with the
                `@CambiumSyntaxKind` macro. The macro will generate the
                `SyntaxKind` conformance from the cases you add next.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-01-empty.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Add the dynamic-text token kinds. Their text varies per
                occurrence â€” a number literal can be `1` or `42`,
                whitespace can be a single space or several lines â€” so the
                parser will pass an explicit text string to the builder
                whenever it emits one of these.

                Each case needs an explicit `UInt32` raw value; gaps
                between dynamic, static, and node ranges keep schema
                evolution easy to spot.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-02-dynamic-tokens.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Add the static-text token kinds â€” operators, parentheses,
                and the `round` keyword â€” annotated with
                `@StaticText(...)`. The macro folds the literal into a
                `staticText(for:)` lookup, so the parser will emit these
                kinds without restating the text at the call site.

                Static-text tokens are deduplicated globally inside the
                builder's interner: two `+` tokens share one byte buffer.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-03-static-text.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Add the node kinds. A node is an internal grouping of
                tokens and child nodes; the parser declares one whenever
                it descends into a syntactic category. `root` is
                mandatory and wraps the whole document. `missing` and
                `error` are sentinels the parser will use when input is
                incomplete or unexpected â€” keeping these in the kind
                enum (rather than out-of-tree state) is what lets a
                Cambium tree round-trip malformed source.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-04-nodes.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Conform to SyntaxLanguage") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage`` is the contract Cambium's
            generic types are parameterized by. It binds a kind enum to
            the runtime distinguished kinds (`rootKind`, `missingKind`,
            `errorKind`), a serialization identity, and the predicates
            Cambium uses to classify trivia, nodes, and tokens during
            traversal.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add a `CalculatorLanguage` enum that conforms to
                `SyntaxLanguage`. Most of the protocol's requirements
                have default implementations, so the conformance reduces
                to: nominate the distinguished kinds, declare a
                serialization identity, and (in the next step) provide
                kind classifiers.

                The `serializationID` and `serializationVersion` are
                stable identifiers persisted with green snapshots â€” keep
                them out of test code so refactors do not silently
                invalidate saved trees.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-05-conformance-basics.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Add the kind classifiers. ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage/isTrivia(_:)``
                marks trivia tokens (whitespace, comments) so traversal
                APIs can skip them. ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage/isNode(_:)``
                and ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage/isToken(_:)`` partition
                every kind into "internal grouping" or "leaf with text."
                The default classifiers treat any kind with static text as
                a token, which would misclassify `number` and `realNumber`
                â€” both *dynamic*-text tokens â€” so we override both.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-06-classifiers.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Finally, add a small grammar-specific extension. The
                parser will use `binaryPrecedence` for Pratt-style
                operator climbing; the typed AST will use
                `isExpressionNode` to filter expression-shaped children
                from the root.

                These extensions live next to the kind enum because they
                interpret the grammar, not because they are part of the
                Cambium contract.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorLanguage.swift", file: "01-language-07-helpers.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Assessments {
        @MultipleChoice {
            Why does `CalculatorLanguage` override `isToken(_:)` and
            `isNode(_:)` rather than relying on the default classifiers?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                The default classifiers crash on enums that have a
                `root` case.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Cambium's defaults handle the `root` case fine. The
                    issue lies elsewhere.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                The default classifier treats kinds without static text
                as nodes, which would misclassify the dynamic-text
                `number` and `realNumber` tokens.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    The default `isToken` returns `true` only for kinds
                    with static text, so dynamic-text leaves get
                    misclassified as nodes. We override both predicates
                    to be explicit.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Cambium requires both classifiers to be defined manually
                for every grammar.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Both predicates have default implementations on
                    ``CambiumCore/SyntaxLanguage``. A grammar with only
                    static-text tokens can rely on the defaults.
                }
            }
        }

        @MultipleChoice {
            What does `@StaticText("+")` change about the kind it
            annotates?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                It tells the parser to skip the kind entirely.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `@StaticText` is purely declarative â€” the parser
                    still emits these tokens.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                It folds the literal into the macro-generated
                `staticText(for:)`, letting the parser call
                `staticToken(.plus)` instead of `token(.plus, text: "+")`.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    The text comes from the language definition, so the
                    parser does not have to repeat it. Mismatched
                    `token`/`staticToken` calls are caught at the call
                    site by the builder.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                It promotes the kind to a node kind.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `@StaticText` only attaches the literal text â€” the
                    kind remains a token kind.
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
